.TH "ASYNCDISPOSABLESTACK.ADOPT" "3JS" "July 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
AsyncDisposableStack.adopt \- AsyncDisposableStack.prototype.adopt()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]adopt()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]AsyncDisposableStack\f[R] instances registers a value that
doesn\(cqt implement the async disposable protocol to the stack by
providing a custom disposer function.
.PP
See \f[CR]DisposableStack.prototype.adopt()\f[R] for general information
about the \f[CR]adopt()\f[R] method.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
adopt(value, onDispose)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]value\f[R]
Any value to be registered to the stack.
.TP
\f[B]onDispose\f[R]
A function that will be called when the stack is disposed.
The function receives \f[CR]value\f[R] as its only argument, and it can
return a promise which gets awaited.
.SS Return value
The same \f[CR]value\f[R] that was passed in.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if \f[CR]onDispose\f[R] is not a function.
.TP
\f[B]ReferenceError\f[R]
Thrown if the stack is already disposed.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using adopt()
This function creates a file handle (as a Node.js \c
.UR https://nodejs.org/api/fs.html#class-filehandle
\f[CR]FileHandle\f[R]
.UE \c
), that gets closed when the function completes.
We suppose that the file handle does not implement the async disposable
protocol (in reality it does), so we use \f[CR]adopt()\f[R] to register
it to the stack.
Because the \f[CR]handle.close()\f[R] method returns a promise, we need
to use an \f[CR]AsyncDisposableStack\f[R] so that the disposal gets
awaited.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]async\f[R] \f[B]function\f[R] readFile(path) {
  \f[B]await\f[R] using disposer = \f[B]new\f[R] AsyncDisposableStack();
  \f[B]const\f[R] handle = disposer.adopt(
    fs.open(path),
    \f[B]async\f[R] (handle) \f[B]=>\f[R] \f[B]await\f[R] handle.close(),
  );
  \f[B]const\f[R] data = \f[B]await\f[R] handle.read();
  \f[I]// The handle.close() method is called and awaited here before exiting\f[R]
  \f[B]return\f[R] data;
}
.EE
